<font color="#FF0000">DEPENDENTS IN VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan  6 21:52:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
  I was a 13 year old civilian dependent in Saigon in 1970, there because my father (who was a civilian working for 7th<br>
Air Force at the time) was stationed at Tan Son Nhut for<br>
a year and had asked my mother and I if we would like to accompany him there for a year. We said, 'Sure,' unaware that we would be there illegally (President Johnson had ordered all dependents out by 1966). <br><br>
  We were surprised to find a small, but thriving civilian community already in place,consisting mainly of dependents of RMK construction families, as well as spook and other civilian families there for mysterious reasons. (We lived on Ho Buu Chan Lane off of Cong Ly Blvd., about 3 miles from Tan Son Nhut.) There were even two high schools there for foreign dependents. One had been there since the early sixties and was called the 'Phoenix' because it had been shelled during Tet '68 and rebuilt, as well as another one run by Baptist missionaries, both of which I attended in 1970. <br><br>
      I am interested in contacting anyone who was in Vienam as a  civilian dependent during the war (ie: as a kid). I have yet to meet anyone since returning who was there in that capacity, but have often entertained the notion of<br>
editing a book of our experiences there because I think<br>
it would be an interesting, but as yet unpublished genre of Vietnam literature. I submitted my story several times to<br>
this web site, but have been unable to locate it so far.<br><br>
